The paper discusses a machine learning approach to differentiate multivariate dynamic signals with limited training data. This problem is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science, including machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computer vision (cs.CV), neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE), and computational linguistics (cs.CL). The paper's focus on self-supervised pre-training and generalization across tasks, datasets, and populations suggests that it is most likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. However, the use of functional neuroimaging data and keyword detection problem also suggests that it may be relevant to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) and computational linguistics (cs.CL) sub-categories. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.CV, cs.NE, and cs.CL, in that order.
